    "In what follows, we put bpol • in correspondence with the category P 2• introduced in subsection 2.2.The Knit functor K -If (φ, f) is a B-map of domain a and codomain b, it follows from 4.1.2(v) that φ(κ a) ⊂ κ b, and therefore φ is a morphism of domain (I, κ a) and codomain (J, κ b).",
    "The association K ∶ a ↦ (I, κ a) for objects and K ∶ (φ, f) ↦ φ for arrows is well defined and is represented by the diagramP 2 • bpol • K (I, κ a) (J, κ b) a b φ φ,f(20)and has the following properties:(i) for every a = ( (I, A,(A i))), κ(id I, id A) = id I (ii) κ(ψ ○ φ, g ○ f) = ψ ○ φ = κ(ψ, g) ○ κ(φ, f) It follows that K ∶ bpol • → P 2• is a functor.The Functor Canon C -In the opposite direction the association C ∶ (I, X) ↦ ca(I, X) for objects and C ∶ φ ↦ (φ, φX Y) for morphisms is represented by the diagramP 2 • bpol • C (I, X) (J, Y) ca(I, X) ca(J, Y) φ φ, φX Y (21) Precisely if φ ∶ (I, X) → (J, Y) is a morphism of p-formations, one has π ca(J,Y) ○ φX Y = φ ○ π ca(I,X).",
    "It follows from Proposition 4.1.2(v), that the couple (φ, φX Y) is a B-map between ca(I, X) and ca(J, Y).",
    "It is easy to verify that C ∶ P 2 0 → bpol • is a functor.The natural transformation π -Lemma 4.2.1 For any p-site a, the parting function of a considered as a map A → κ a, denoted π a, induces a BG-map a → ca(I, κ a)Proof.",
    "Put b ∶= ca(I, κ a), then π b = i κa P(I), Then one has π a = π b ○ π a therefore in view of Proposition 3.2.3(iv)), π a is a BG-map."
